    "<li>Matching fossils across oceans (Mesosaurus, Glossopteris).</li>"
    "<li>Glacial striations in tropical regions.</li></ul>"
    "<h4>Seafloor Spreading</h4>"
    "<ul><li>Mid-ocean ridges produce new oceanic crust.</li>"
    "<li>Magnetic striping: symmetric reversals on either side of ridge.</li>"
    "<li>Age of ocean floor increases with distance from ridge.</li></ul>"
    "<h4>Plate Boundaries</h4>"
    "<ul><li><b>Divergent:</b> Plates move apart → new crust (mid-ocean ridges, rift valleys).</li>"
    "<li><b>Convergent:</b> Plates collide → subduction, mountains, or volcanic arcs.</li>"
    "<li><b>Transform:</b> Plates slide past each other → earthquakes (San Andreas Fault).</li></ul>",
    [("Continental Drift","Wegener's hypothesis that continents were once joined (Pangaea) and have since drifted apart."),
     ("Seafloor Spreading","New oceanic crust forms at mid-ocean ridges as magma rises, pushes plates apart, and solidifies."),
     ("Divergent Boundary","Where plates move apart; new crust forms (mid-ocean ridges) or continents rift apart."),
     ("Convergent Boundary","Where plates collide; denser plate subducts, forming trenches, volcanoes, or mountain ranges."),
     ("Transform Boundary","Where plates slide horizontally past each other; produces earthquakes (e.g., San Andreas Fault).")],
    [("Alfred Wegener proposed continental drift in 1912 but lacked a mechanism. The mechanism is now known as:",["Gravity","Erosion","*Mantle convection driving plate tectonics","Lunar tides"],"Driving force."),
     ("Pangaea was the supercontinent that existed approximately _____ million years ago.",["50","100","*250-300","1,000"],"Pangaea timing."),
     ("Matching Mesosaurus fossils on both South America and Africa support drift because:",["The animal could swim oceans","*The freshwater reptile couldn't cross oceans — the continents must have been joined","It was planted","Random chance"],"Fossil evidence."),
     ("At a divergent boundary, plates move _____ and new crust is _____.",["Together; destroyed","Past each other; unchanged","*Apart; created","Together; created"],"Divergent process."),
     ("The Mid-Atlantic Ridge is an example of a:",["Transform boundary","Convergent boundary","*Divergent boundary (separating the North American and Eurasian plates)","Hotspot"],"MAR."),
     ("When an oceanic plate converges with a continental plate:",["Nothing happens","The continent subducts","*The denser oceanic plate subducts beneath the continental plate","Both plates rise"],"Oceanic-continental."),
     ("The Himalayas formed from the collision of:",["An oceanic and continental plate","*Two continental plates (Indian and Eurasian — neither subducts easily, so rock is pushed upward)","Two oceanic plates","A transform boundary"],"Continental collision."),
     ("The San Andreas Fault is a _____ boundary.",["Divergent","Convergent","*Transform","Subduction"],"Transform fault."),
     ("Magnetic striping on the ocean floor provides evidence for seafloor spreading because:",["Stripes are colorful","*Symmetric magnetic reversals on both sides of the ridge show that new crust forms and moves outward","They're random","They indicate depth"],"Magnetic evidence."),
     ("Ocean crust near mid-ocean ridges is _____ than crust far from ridges.",["Older","Thicker","*Younger","Denser"],"Age pattern."),
     ("Subduction zones often produce:",["Deserts","Flat plains","*Volcanic arcs and deep ocean trenches","Glaciers"],"Subduction features."),
     ("The Ring of Fire encircles the _____ Ocean.",["Atlantic","Indian","*Pacific","Arctic"],"Ring of Fire."),
     ("Tectonic plates move at rates of approximately:",["Meters per day","*Centimeters per year (about as fast as fingernails grow)","Kilometers per year","They don't move"],"Plate speed."),
     ("GPS technology has confirmed plate tectonics by:",["Photographing plates","*Measuring the precise movement of locations over time (matching predicted plate velocities)","Recording earthquakes only","Mapping the ocean floor only"],"Modern evidence."),
     ("A hotspot volcano like Hawaii forms:",["At a plate boundary","*Over a stationary mantle plume as the plate moves over it (creating an island chain)","At a divergent boundary only","Randomly"],"Hotspot mechanism."),
     ("The East African Rift is an example of:",["A convergent boundary","A transform fault","*Continental rifting (a divergent boundary splitting Africa apart)","A stable region"],"Continental rift."),
     ("Convection in the mantle works by:",["Heating at the top","*Hot material rising from the core region, cooling at the surface, and sinking — creating circulation cells","Random movement","Only lateral flow"],"Convection process."),
     ("The oldest oceanic crust is about 200 million years old. Continental crust can be:",["Younger","The same age","*Over 4 billion years old (oceanic crust is recycled by subduction, continents persist)","200 million years too"],"Crust age comparison."),
     ("Plate tectonics theory unified which earlier ideas?",["Only continental drift","Only seafloor spreading","*Both continental drift AND seafloor spreading into a comprehensive theory","Neither"],"Unifying theory."),
     ("Plate tectonics is fundamental because it explains:",["Only volcanoes","Only earthquakes","Only mountain building","*The distribution of earthquakes, volcanoes, mountains, ocean basins, and even climate patterns"],"Comprehensive explanation.")]
